The utility method is not going to know about the fields in the main class, like `uniformOne`, `uniformTwo` etc. So unless you want to get into reflection territory, you have to take a consumer of some kind, and the caller will use that to assign its fields.

If you want to just make a more general version of what you currently have in `onRegister`, consider using a `Map&lt;String, ShaderUniform&gt;` to store all the uniforms instead, rather than individual fields. The utility method can easily produce such a map from a list of uniform names that you can pass as varargs.

Instead of

    public ShaderUniform uniformOne, uniformTwo, uniformThree;

Declare

    private Map&lt;String, ShaderUniform&gt; uniforms;

And perhaps add a public method that allows getting uniforms by their names.

The utility method can then be:

```
public static void registerShader(RegisterShadersEvent event, String path, BiConsumer&lt;ShaderInstance, Map&lt;String, ShaderUniform&gt;&gt; block, String... uniformNames) {
    event.registerShader(ShaderInstance.create(path), s -&gt; {
        var shaderInstance = (ShaderInstance)s;
        var uniformMap = Arrays.stream(uniformNames)
            .collect(Collectors.toMap(Function.identity(), 
                     shaderInstance::getUniform));
        block.accept(shaderInstance, uniformMap);
    });
}
```

You&#39;d use it like this in the main class:

```
registerShader(event, &quot;path/to/shader.fsh&quot;, (shader, map) -&gt; {
    this.shader = shader;
    this.uniforms = map;
}, &quot;One&quot;, &quot;Two&quot;, &quot;Three&quot;);
```

I&#39;m not sure what library you are working with, but if the `s` in the consumer is always the instance you create in the second argument i.e. `ShaderInstance.create(path)`, then you probably don&#39;t need to pass that to the consumer. You can just return that directly:

```
public static ShaderInstance registerShader(RegisterShadersEvent event, String path, Consumer&lt;ShaderInstance, Map&lt;String, ShaderUniform&gt;&gt; block, String... uniformNames) {
    var shader = ShaderInstance.create(path);
    event.registerShader(shader, s -&gt; {
        var uniformMap = Arrays.stream(uniformNames)
            .collect(Collectors.toMap(Function.identity(), 
                     shader::getUniform));
        block.accept(uniformMap);
    });
    return shader;
}

// Usage:
this.shader = registerShader(
    event, &quot;path/to/shader.fsh&quot;, 
    map -&gt; this.uniforms = map,
    &quot;One&quot;, &quot;Two&quot;, &quot;Three&quot;);
```

